title: Single-Dose, Dose-Escalation Study With LY3303560 to Evaluate the Safety, Tolerability, and Pharmacokinetics in Healthy Subjects and Patients With Mild Cognitive Impairment Due to Alzheimer's Disease or Mild to Moderate Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief:
The purpose of this study is to evaluate the safety and tolerability of the study drug, LY3303560. Side effects and laboratory results will be monitored. This study will involve single doses of LY3303560 administered intravenously (IV), meaning into a vein or subcutaneously (SC), meaning under the skin.

Screening is required within 28 days before the start of the study for healthy participants and within 70 days before the start of the study for AD participants. The study requires about 16 weeks of each participant's time including a 4 day clinical research unit (CRU) admission and 10 follow-up appointments.

This is the first time that this study drug is being given to participants. This study is for research purposes only, and is not intended to treat any medical condition.

explanation_target: Reason: The investigational agent LY3303560 is zagotenemab, a humanized monoclonal (immunotherapy) that preferentially binds misfolded/aggregated tau and is intended to block or delay transcellular spread of pathological tau — i.e., it targets AD pathology rather than only symptomatic cognition. citeturn0search5turn0search3

Act: Evidence from preclinical and clinical reports describes LY3303560 (zagotenemab) as an anti‑tau antibody with high affinity for tau aggregates and with the hypothesized disease‑modifying action of reducing tau spread/aggregation. Key sources: AAIC preclinical abstract describing selectivity for aggregated tau, an institutional/registry summary, and a Phase I/IB safety/pharmacokinetic paper. citeturn0search0turn0search1turn0search5

Reflect: Given the drug is a monoclonal antibody directed at tau aggregates (a core Alzheimer’s pathology) it fits the definition of a "disease‑targeted biologic." I reviewed preclinical characterization and early clinical safety reports to confirm mechanism and intent; no indication the agent is a small molecule, symptomatic cognitive enhancer, or primarily for neuropsychiatric symptom relief. citeturn0search0turn0search5

Web search results used (titles/sources): 1) "Safety, Tolerability, and Pharmacokinetics of Zagotenemab...: A Phase I Clinical Trial" (PMC / PubMed Central). citeturn0search5 2) "Zagotenemab | ALZFORUM" (therapy profile). citeturn0search3 3) "Preclinical characterization of an antibody [LY3303560] targeting aggregated tau" (AAIC/Alzheimer's & Dementia abstract). citeturn0search0 4) HRA research summary referencing LY3303560 and tau effects. citeturn0search1
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational agent LY3303560 (zagotenemab) is a humanized monoclonal antibody that preferentially binds misfolded/aggregated extracellular tau and is intended to block or delay transcellular spread of pathological tau — i.e., it directly targets tau pathology in AD. citeturn0search0turn0search2

Act: Extracted details — drug: LY3303560 (zagotenemab); mechanism: anti‑tau monoclonal antibody selective for aggregated/misfolded tau with the hypothesized disease‑modifying action of reducing tau spread/aggregation; clinical context: tested in Phase I and Phase II trials in MCI/mild‑moderate AD. Based on these specifics, assign CADRO category B) Tau. citeturn0search0turn0search2

Reflect: This classification fits CADRO because the intervention specifically targets tau aggregation/spread (a core AD proteinopathy) rather than amyloid, inflammation, synaptic receptors, or a symptomatic mechanism. The trial description and primary literature consistently characterize zagotenemab as an anti‑tau antibody, so 'B) Tau' is the most specific and appropriate CADRO category (not multi‑target or non‑therapeutic). citeturn0search0turn0search3
